                            <comment id="12767668" author="jdcryans" created="Tue, 20 Oct 2009 03:03:15 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I tried this patch on trunk and it passed on Hudson. Now we cache the DNS resolution enabling us to instantiate a lot less objects and saving us from DNS negative caching. That&apos;s ok with you guys?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12767675" author="apurtell" created="Tue, 20 Oct 2009 03:44:37 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;The -v3 patch fixes the issues I&apos;m seeing on 0.20 branch also. &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12767677" author="jdcryans" created="Tue, 20 Oct 2009 03:53:43 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Committed. Sorry for the problems, unfortunately my machine&apos;s configuration was different in a way that the tests didn&apos;t fail for me on the second patch.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12767679" author="stack" created="Tue, 20 Oct 2009 03:59:00 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;So, once cached, it can never change.  I suppose this is fine.  Maybe one day when we grow up and we have hbase clusters of 1k hosts and we need to support machines changing IPs, we can use something like &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.xbill.org/dnsjava/&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;http://www.xbill.org/dnsjava/&lt;/a&gt; to manage our dns cache.  Meantime, patch looks good to me. +1.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
